<author><name><![CDATA[Bregalad]]></name></author>
<updated>2014-03-30T03:26:57-07:00</updated>
<published>2014-03-30T03:26:57-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11129&amp;p=127269#p127269</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11129&amp;p=127269#p127269"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Mapper #118 question]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11129&amp;p=127269#p127269"><![CDATA[
The mapper doesn't change anything. It's simply that the PPU access different regions of memory depending on which nametables and which tiles are fetched, and the mapper redirect those addresses to different part of physical memory.<br /><br />On a standard (mapper #4) MMC3 cart, the MMC3 distinguishes reads from $0000-$1fff (pattern table fetches) and reads from $2000-$2fff (nametable fetches), and does a different &quot;remapping&quot; in function of which fetch it is : On pattern table fetches it uses the CHR banking registers, but on nametable fetches it uses the mirroring bit.<br /><br />On mapper #118, the mirroring wire is not connected and is connected to a CHR banking address line instead. It's as if all fetches were from $0000-$1fff, even if they are actually nametable fetches at $2000-$2ffff, that's why/how the CHR banking regs also control mirroring in a weird way.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=38">Bregalad</a> — Sun Mar 30, 2014 3:26 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
